{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"add8de0e-1d5a-486e-b35d-77edff5d2d77","content":"Use **`dotnet workload update`**. It updates all installed workloads to the versions matching your current SDK, which is exactly what's needed after an SDK update.\n\n**`dotnet workload repair`** only reinstalls the *same* versions — it fixes corrupted installs but won't pull in the newer workload packages your updated SDK expects.\n\nQuick fix:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf your project or repo includes a `global.json` or workload manifest, consider `dotnet workload restore` instead — it installs the exact workload versions pinned by the project, which is more reproducible across machines.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ea7a6ffb-4f99-415e-8e71-6ff86d664a11","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after a SDK update broke their build.\n\nThis is a general knowledge question, not a codebase task. I can answer directly.\n\n- `dotnet workload update` — updates all installed workloads to the latest available versions for the installed SDK. This is what you want after a SDK update, because the workload versions may lag behind the SDK.\n- `dotnet workload repair` — reinstalls all installed workloads to fix corrupted installations, but doesn't update them to newer versions.\n\nAfter a .NET SDK update, the typical fix is `dotnet workload update` (or sometimes `dotnet workload restore` if using a workload manifest in the project).","outputTokens":344,"requestId":"3C2C:2A0528:D55B81:108F0D6:6A0128B9"},"id":"4020ecc6-a4f2-496d-8cb3-8a879ce848ec","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:54:26.288Z","parentId":"16f54751-2b45-4e79-b13e-c5c822d77b08"}
